# Wedding Planner MVP Requirements

Build a demo-ready MVP in phases, preserving current stack and avoiding unnecessary rewrites.

## Working Style
- Build incrementally in phases.
- Before coding each step, state what you will build, files touched, and why.
- After each step, provide code location and concise test instructions.
- Stub API-dependent behavior with mock data and TODOs.
- Keep business logic separate from presentation.
- Enforce role-based access in UI and logic.

## Roles and Access
- Planner: manage clients, vendors, workflow, tasks, and internal progress.
- Manager/Admin: planner capabilities plus full internal clock-in/timelog visibility.
- Couple: read-only view of own event data except messaging.
- Couple users cannot see internal timelogs, staff-only notes, or unrelated clients.

## Must-Have MVP Areas
- Clients Working View with urgency queue and next-action guidance.
- Prioritization labels: Critical, High, Do soon, Normal, Waiting.
- Stage requirement gates and blocked-stage explanations.
- Planner dashboard (clients, upcoming deadlines, vendors, budgets, billable visibility).
- Client detail view with workflow progression, blockers, vendor/budget/time snapshots.
- Vendor management with waiting/follow-up statuses and manual add flow.
- Couple portal (checklist, budget, vendor/venue/progress, messaging).
- Time tracking with strict role visibility rules.
- Budget health states (healthy, warning, over budget).
- Venue as separate entity (not permanently only a vendor category).

## Future-Ready Shells
- Recommended Vendors section with mock/stub + TODO API hook.
- AI layout/flooring/venue visualizer placeholder with mock sample cards.
- Keep data models extensible for future real API + AI integrations.

## Delivery Phases
- Phase 1: architecture, models, routes, permissions, stage-gate engine structure.
- Phase 2: core planner/couple UI pages.
- Phase 3: business rules and workflow validation logic.
- Phase 4: AI placeholders, follow-up prompts, and demo polish.
